Help.Tip: Menu allowing user choice of stored parameter defaults.
Help.Text:
svi - PROCESSDEFAULTS
Menu allowing user choice of stored parameter defaults.
 
 Default = SYSTEM
 Allowed = SYSTEM
 Allowed = PROJECT
 Allowed = USER
 SYSTEM defaults are the defaults listed in the CPS documentation.
 
 PROJECT defaults are defaults the user has saved via the Save as Project
 Default button.
 
 USER defaults are defaults the user has saved via the Save as User Default
 button.

Help.Tip: Type of norm, average or RMS, to use in inversion.
Help.Text:
svi - NORM_TYPE
Type of norm, average or RMS, to use in inversion.
 
 Default = RMS
 Allowed = RMS, AVG
 
 Choose RMS when the input is RMS velocity.  Choose AVG when the input
 is average velocity.

Help.Tip: Maximum number of outer loop iterations.
Help.Text:
svi - NITER_OUTER
Maximum number of outer loop iterations.
 
 Default = 300
 Allowed = integer scalar >= 1
 
 Limits the number of iterations when model convergence is too slow.

Help.Tip: Maximum number of conjugate gradient iterations.
Help.Text:
svi - NITER_CG
Maximum number of conjugate gradient iterations.
 
 Default = 3
 Allowed = integer scalar >= 1
 
 The number of iterations used in the conjugate gradient solver.  Recommend
 using the default value.

Help.Tip: Relaxation parameter.
Help.Text:
svi - RELAXATION
Relaxation parameter.
 
 Default = 1.
 Allowed = 1. <= real scalar <= 2.
 
 Controls rate of convergence.  Recommend using the default value.

Help.Tip: Regularization parameter.
Help.Text:
svi - SLAMBDA
Regularization parameter.
 
 Default = 3.
 Allowed = real scalar >= 0.
 
 Regularization parameter.  Recommend using the default value.

Help.Tip: Stopping criteria.
Help.Text:
svi - STOP_CRITERIA
Stopping criteria.
 
 Default = 8.
 Allowed = real scalar >= 0.
 
 Stopping criteria.  Recommend using the default value.

Help.Tip: Maximum negative slowness perturbation (ms/ft or ms/m).
Help.Text:
svi - NEGMAXPERT
Maximum negative slowness perturbation (ms/ft or ms/m).
 
 Default = -0.4
 Allowed = real scalar
 
 Maximum negative slowness perturbation in ms/ft or ms/m.

Help.Tip: Maximum positive slowness perturbation (ms/ft or ms/m).
Help.Text:
svi - POSMAXPERT
Maximum positive slowness perturbation (ms/ft or ms/m).
 
 Default = 0.4
 Allowed = real scalar
 
 Maximum positive slowness perturbation in ms/ft or ms/m.

Help.Tip: Percent padding added to end of velocity function.
Help.Text:
svi - PADDING_PERC
Percent padding added to end of velocity function.
 
 Default = 15.
 Allowed = real scalar >= 0.
 
 Padding added to end of velocity function in percent of velocity function
 length.  Recommend using the default value.

Help.Tip: Diagnostic output.
Help.Text:
svi - DIAGNOSTICS
Diagnostic output.
 
 Default = OFF
 Allowed = ON, OFF
 
 Controls output of diagnostic output.

Help.Tip: Choose DIAG_FILE using a file selection dialog box.
Help.Text:
svi - SELECT_DIAG_FILE
Choose DIAG_FILE using a file selection dialog box.

Help.Tip: Pathname for diagnostic output file.
Help.Text:
svi - DIAG_FILE
Pathname for diagnostic output file.
 
 Default = NONE
 Allowed = char
 
 For parallel jobs, the worker number is appended to the name of the file.

Help.Tip: Status of DIAG_FILE.
Help.Text:
svi - DIAG_FILE_INFO
Status of DIAG_FILE.

 Menu that allows the user to accept the current parameter values, run the

Accept the current parameters and move to the next process.

 Button that saves the current parameter values as Project Defaults for this

svi - USERDEFAULT
Save the current parameter values as User Defaults.
 
 Default =
 Allowed =
 Button that saves the current parameter values as User Defaults for this

Allows the user to access the pop-up Help Window.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                         C P S   P R O C E S S
 
 Name       : SVI
 Category   : Inversion
 Written    : 2004-06-29   by: bkmacy
 Revised    : 2006-10-16   by: D. Glover
 Maturity   : production
 Purpose    : Stacking velocity inversion.
 Portability: No known limitations.
 Parallel   : Yes.
 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          GENERAL DESCRIPTION
 
 SVI performs stacking velocity inversion using constrained Dix inversion.
 The input is stacking velocities as a function of two-way traveltime, and
 the output is interval velocities as a function of two-way traveltime.
 The input velocities are assumed to be equivalent to RMS average velocities
 (for NORM_TYPE=RMS) or straight average velocities (for NORM_TYPE=AVG).
 
 The inversion algorithm operates on a single velocity function at a time.
 No lateral smoothing or mixing is performed.  This is a 1-D algorithm.
 
 This process is based on the SVI program originally developed by Chong
 Chung.
 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          ADVICE FOR USERS
 
 SVI assumes that stacking velocities are equivalent to RMS average velocites
 (for NORM_TYPE=RMS) or straight average velocities (for NORM_TYPE=AVG).
 For example, using DMO velocities will be better than NMO velocities.
